The term "materialistic" often has a negative connotation. Labeling a person as being materialistic can create a perception of an individual that they place higher value in possessions over other people or experiences. Society may also determine that the individual places higher priority on spending money rather than saving it towards what others believe to be a better purpose. Materialism, however, is a necessary quality that provides more benefits than it is perceived to take away from society.

A person who places higher value in possessions and spending money is constantly contributing to the local and global economy. For example, a materialistic person who purchases a car is directly helping to sustain a car business, keep a car salesperson in a job, and pay taxes that will go towards funding education and other programs needed in society. In using that car, the person is buying gas that will keep a gas station in business and employ workers for the gas station, gas haulers, oil workers, and others. Inevitably, the car will need work done that will ensure automotive repair shops are kept in business along with their employees.
